Part 1: Defining Phase 1 Outcomes and Phase 2 Scope¶

Part 1.1: Phase 1 Summary¶

Part 1.1.1: Dataset Information and Source¶

This project's purpose is to predict the Total ESG Score (our target feature, esgR) for constiuents to the Standard&Poor 500 Index (the index) based on metrics utilised by Industry participants in defining Investment Performance and Company Performance, in combination with categorical information regarding the constituents Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) categorisation.

The Phase One (p1) report of this project provided:

  • A high-level explanation of the data's content and source,

  • Instructions on preprocessing and cleaning the data,

  • Summary information regarding categorical and quantitative variables,

  • A Multi-faceted visual exploration of the inter-play between different variables.

The contents of the data were defined by global rating agency Standard & Poor (SP) as the S&P500 index (the index) which observed 501 index constituents as at January 2023. These observations represented 11 of 11 Sectors and 118 of 163 Industries. (spglobal, 2023).

These observations were uniquely identified by their stock symbols (symbols, primary key) and formed the spine of what would be become this reports working dataframe whose breadth covers each observations;

  • Operational Domicile (GICS sector & industry)

  • Non-Financial Risk Metrics (ESG and Controversy Ratings),

  • Financial Risk Metrics (Invesment Performance and Accounting Metrics).

Part 1.1.2: Data Cleaning and Processing¶

Data wrangling and pre-processing outlined 421 complete cases of a total 501 possible for further inference through the following process;

Data Processing;

  1. Employed a script to scrape the Morningstar Sustainalytics scores from yahoofinance (Rudden, 2019)

  2. Pulled adjusted close prices for each listed security (yfinance),

  3. Calculated Investment Performance Metrics (invPerf),

  4. Pulled accounting performance information (WHAT PACKAGE),

  5. Merged the three dataframes into one for analysis,

Data Cleaning;

  1. Separated rows with missing values in any of the variables to a separate frame for gap analysis,

  2. Preserved the unique keys by moving them out of the df itself and instead to rownames,

  3. Reviewed summary statistics for Quantitative and Qualitative information,

  4. Defined the target feature as Total ESG Rating and research objectives.

Part 1.1.3: Data Exploration and Visualisation¶

Across these observations, exploratory data analysis indicated a breadth and width to the numeric and categorical variables in the frame, whose values were then graphically illustrated presenting;

  1. A single-variable chart illustrating the sector-level breakdown by relative frequency for which sectors were more and less represented within the data.(Fig 1, App. A1),

  2. A single-variable chart illustrating the sector-level breakdown by relative frequency denoting how campy observations each sector was missing across the data (Fig 2, App. A2),

  3. A two-variable boxplot indicating the spread and distribution of Total ESG Scores by sector (Fig 3, App. A3),

  4. A two-variable boxplot indicating the spread and distribution of Market Capitalisation by sector (Fig 4, App. A4),

  5. A three-variable scatter plot indicating the market capitalisation per sector faceted by controversy level(Fig 5, App. A5), and

  6. A three-variable inverted boxplot which demonstrated how relative Beta risk was when faceted by controversy scores (Fig 6, App. A6).

These charts have been indexed as noted above as appendices.

Part 1.2: Phase Two Report Overview¶

The segmentation of this report's process and findings sits across the following sections; defining scope, discovering output, discussing limitations, and determination of findings.

Part 1.2.1: Defining Scope¶

Continuing on from Phase 1, this report for Phase 2 (p2) considers the construction and analysis of a regression model employed to predict the index constituents esgR score (the target) based on categorical GICS information (Sector, Industry) and financial risk and reward measures contained within the data (the predictors).

Part 1.2.2: Discovering output¶

Initial steps are taken to conclude data preparation by one-hot encoding categorical variables and standardizing numeric variables prior to measurement.

Initailly, Linear Regession models utilising Mutual Informatino and Correlation for feature selection are presented in contrast illustrating the relative differences in importance on a feature for feature basis. All 18 features are included and commentary is offered as to each respective makeup. Both linear models are scored by Mean Aboslute Error and R-Squared for the full sequence of feautres and illustrations are employed to contextualise the relationship between scoring and number of features included.

A comprehensive review is then conducted where Linear, Gradient Boosting, Decision Tree, and Random Forest regression models are scored by MAE and RSQ across both Correlation and Mutual Information methods providing contrasting context to how each iteration sits relatively. All values are then displayed measuring each models individual relationship between RSQ and number of features.

Two different models are identified to the model performance analysis where each is processed through random and grid search cross-validation techniques across 5 folds. The relative scores and features are organised and contrast against the respective model identified in the feature selection stage.

Model performance analysis then employs both grid and random search cross-validation methods on a feature-for-feature basis to review against benchmark models identified through feature selection. Relative performance is contrast and commentary speaks to what differences arise between the CV outputs and the feature selection approach.

Model comparison takes the form of utilising paired t-tests, testing the mean to determine the likelihood of a non-zero difference between the mean values of feature importance, and model predictions. These differences are visualised and final commentary leads into the discussion on limitations to the research.

Part 1.3: Overview of Methodology¶

The underlying methodology of this phase is that of tuning and training a regression model to predict the total ESG Ratings for SP500 companies in the index as at January 2023.

The methodolody is broken into Data Preparation, and Discovery phases as below;

Part 1.3.1: Data preparation for preditctive modelling¶

Data was prepared the for predictive modelling by manipulating the data to ensure;

  • Categorical variables are processed via;

    • One-hot encoding (nominal; sector, indusrty), and
    • Integer-encoding (ordinal; controversy level).

  • Numeric features are appropiately scaled by;

    • Applying robust scaling to better deal with outliers in predictor variables discovered in Phase 1, this way the mean absolute deviation will be a more approrpriate measure for companies whose measures sit magnitudes above others.

Now with everything pointing the right way, data was split for training:testing (4:1) and a random state (21, this group number) was assigned for reproducability. Data was not sampled due to existing sample size being relatively small to begin with.

Part 1.3.2: Discovering Best Fit (Part 2)¶

Feature Selection (FS) is initially performed on a linear (LN) regression model utilising two methods; correlation (CR) and mutual information (MI). All predictor variables are reviewed for their value to the overall model.

Observations are made as to how the best features vary between FS methods for the LN model with light discussion on their relevance to the overall project purpose.

MAE scores for both FS methods are graphically represented demonstrating the complexity of the relationship as features selected increase.

A more comprehensive search for model fitting and tuning is then undertaken where Random Forest (RF), Gradient Boosting (GB), and Decision Tree (DT) regression models are contrast against the initial Linear approach using both Mutual Information and Correlation feature selection methods over the full range of features (1:18).

By starting with the LN model, the strategy is to derive a benchmark for contrasting the more sophisticated methods (RF,DT,GB). All models are then scored by Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and R-squared (RSQ) in order to determine a best-in-class fit.

One model scoring best over both measures is identified and carried forward for a Cross-Validation (CV) with a second model scoring a similar RSQ with less features into a model performance comparison where both regression models are used to benchmark the grid search (GS) and random search (RS) CV scores across the full suite of features measuring both RSQ and MAE.

Succinct performance commentary is provided relative to each best-in-class model as well as well as on a feature-for-feature basis.

Paired t-tests are then conducted to compare similarities between feature importance in cross-validation results as well as the predictions agaisnt each model relative to each cross-validation method.

Part 2: Discovery¶

The underlying task is to seek to understand how well one may predict non-financial risk based on financial risk features. The inclusion of categorical variables is intended to facet financial risk measures working from an assumption that constituent specific performance may vary by GICS sector.

This is confirmed in Appendix B where the data are grouped by sector and numeric variables have summay statistics run through ANOVA.

One-hot encoding the sector variable has increased the shape from 11 to a total of 18 variables on a length of 421 observations.

The strategy here-in is to move from simple through to more sophisticated models reviewing all options in order to consider the context for a best-in-class model.

Part 2.1: Feature Selection¶

Starting at simple, the first approach to modeling the available features in the data involves reviewing a linear (LN) regression model utilising two methods of Feature Selection (FS); correlation (CR) and mutual information (MI). These FS methods have been chosen due to the target variable being continuous.

This first approach (LN w/CR & MI) will serve as a benchmark by regressing against all features (18) affording insight to how important each feature is.

Part 2.1.1: Feature Selection by Correlation for Linear Regression¶

Figure 1a visualises exponentially decreasing correlation from left to right, with the higher and more important features sitting to the left.

Four features sit over 30% with the three highest being categorical (Controversy, Energy Sector and Real Estate Sector), and the fourth being log returns over 1 year. After this there is a steep shift that see's market capitalisation and Earnings Per Share (EPS), two financial metrics, scoring lowest overall.

Part 2.1.3: Reviewing Linear Regression MAE Scores¶

Figure 2a illustrates a de-identifed progression in MAE scoring which offers context as to the respective trajectories both FS methods track.

It is observed that both do not follow a continued rate of change, with both offering steep descent from features 1 through 5, before then respectively increasing MAE scores for a short stretch, before ultimately continuing a descent to the same resting place noted above.

Correlation based FS dips lowest at 10 features, which are identified in Fig 1a being; ControversyLevel, 7 of 11 Sectors (Energy, Real Estate, Information Technology, Utilities, Materials, Industrials, and Consumer Discretionary), and finally 2 financial risk measures (LnRet_1y, StDev_3y). This indicates that the correlation feature selection is largely scoring based on the GICS sector that an index constituent operates within.

At 10 features, the Mutual Information based FS curve reduces further to its lowest point at 14 features, however, for immediate like for like contrast the best 10 features for MI have 3 of the top 4 being financial risk measures, before again being filled out by sectors with controversy being 10th.

# Task 2.1, Fig 2
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.datasets import make_regression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_regression, mutual_info_regression
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# DEF FUN EVAL MODEL
def evaluate_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, method, k):
    # DEF feature selection
    X_train_fs, X_test_fs, fs = method(X_train, y_train, X_test, k)
    # FIT model
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_train_fs, y_train)
    # REV model
    yhat = model.predict(X_test_fs)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, yhat)
    return mae

# DEF FUN FS CR
def select_feat_Correl(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    fsCorrel = SelectKBest(score_func=f_regression, k=k)
    fsCorrel.fit(X_train, y_train)
    X_train_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_train)
    X_test_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsCorrel, X_test_fsCorrel, fsCorrel

# DEF FUN FS MI
def select_feat_mutInfo(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    # DEF feature selection
    fsMutInfo = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_regression, k=k)
    # GET relationship from training data
    fsMutInfo.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # TFR train input data
    X_train_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_train)
    # TFR test input data
    X_test_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsMutInfo, X_test_fsMutInfo, fsMutInfo

# DEF df for results
results_df_MAE_by_feature = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Method', 'Features', 'MAE'])

for k in range(1, 19):  # LOOP THRU: 1 to 18
    # EVAL FS CR
    mae_correl = evaluate_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, select_feat_Correl, k)
    results_df_MAE_by_feature = results_df_MAE_by_feature.append({'Method': 'fsCorrel', 'Features': k, 'MAE': mae_correl}, ignore_index=True)
    # EVAL FS MI
    mae_mutinfo = evaluate_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, select_feat_mutInfo, k)
    results_df_MAE_by_feature = results_df_MAE_by_feature.append({'Method': 'fsMutInfo', 'Features': k, 'MAE': mae_mutinfo}, ignore_index=True)

# 'Method' and 'Features'

# Task 2.1, Fig 2b
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.datasets import make_regression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_regression, mutual_info_regression
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# DEF FUN EVAL MODEL
def evaluate_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, method, k):
    # DEF feature selection
    X_train_fs, X_test_fs, fs = method(X_train, y_train, X_test, k)
    # FIT model
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_train_fs, y_train)
    # REV model
    yhat = model.predict(X_test_fs)
    rsq = r2_score(y_test, yhat)
    return rsq

# DEF FUN FS CR
def select_feat_Correl(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    # DEF feature selection
    fsCorrel = SelectKBest(score_func=f_regression, k=k)
    # GET relationship from training
    fsCorrel.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # TFR train input data
    X_train_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_train)
    # TFR test input data
    X_test_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsCorrel, X_test_fsCorrel, fsCorrel

# DEF FUN FS MI
def select_features_mutInfo(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    # DEF feature selection
    fsMutInfo = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_regression, k=k)
    # GET relationship from training data
    fsMutInfo.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # TFR train input data
    X_train_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_train)
    # TFR test input data
    X_test_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsMutInfo, X_test_fsMutInfo, fsMutInfo

# DEF df for results
results_df_rsq_by_feature = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Method', 'Features', 'rsq'])

for k in range(1, 19):  # LOOP THRU: 1 to 18
    # EVAL FS CR

    # EVAL FS MI

    results_df_rsq_by_feature = results_df_rsq_by_feature.append({'Method': 'fsMutInfo', 'Features': k, 'rsq': rsq_mutinfo}, ignore_index=True)

# Task 2.1: Feature Selection ALL

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, r2_score
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_regression, mutual_info_regression

# DEF Function: correlation-based FS
def select_features_correl(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    fsCorrel = SelectKBest(score_func=f_regression, k=k)
    fsCorrel.fit(X_train, y_train)
    X_train_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_train)
    X_test_fsCorrel = fsCorrel.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsCorrel, X_test_fsCorrel

# DEF Function: mutual information-based FS
def select_features_mutual(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    fsMutInfo = SelectKBest(score_func=mutual_info_regression, k=k)
    fsMutInfo.fit(X_train, y_train)
    X_train_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_train)
    X_test_fsMutInfo = fsMutInfo.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fsMutInfo, X_test_fsMutInfo

# SET models
ln_model = LinearRegression(random_state=21)
dt_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=21)
rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=21)
gb_model = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=21)

# DEF N of feat to consider
k_features_range = range(1, 19)  # RANGE values from 1 to 18

# SET an empty list to store the results
results = []

# RUN through each N of k_features
for k in k_features_range:
    # GET correlation-based FS
    X_train_fsCorrel, X_test_fsCorrel = select_features_correl(X_train, y_train, X_test, k)
    
    # GET models to iterate over
    models = [ln_model, dt_model, rf_model, gb_model]
    model_names = ['Linear', 'Decision Tree', 'Random Forest', 'Gradient Boosting']
    
    # FIT models and calc R-squared values for correlation-based
    for model, model_name in zip(models, model_names):
        model.fit(X_train_fsCorrel, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_fsCorrel)
        r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
        mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
        # ADD result to the list
        results.append({
            'Regression Type': model_name,
            'Feature Selection Method': 'Correlation',
            'Number of Features': k,
            'R-squared': r2,
            'Mean Abs Err':mae
        })
    
    # GET mutual information-based FS
    X_train_fsMutInfo, X_test_fsMutInfo = select_features_mutual(X_train, y_train, X_test, k)
    
    # FIT models and calc R-squared values for mutual information-based
    for model, model_name in zip(models, model_names):
        model.fit(X_train_fsMutInfo, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test_fsMutInfo)
        r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
        mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
        # ADD result to the list
        results.append({
            'Regression Type': model_name,
            'Feature Selection Method': 'Mutual Information',
            'Number of Features': k,
            'R-squared': r2,
            'Mean Abs Err':mae
        })

# # DEF DataFrame to store the results
results_comp = pd.DataFrame(results)

# ORG the DataFrame by R-squared in descending order
results_comp = results_comp.sort_values(by='R-squared', ascending=False)

# REM negative values out
results_comp = results_comp[results_comp['R-squared'] > 0]

Part 2.1.5: Reviewing All Models and FS Methods by RSQ¶

Figure 3 illustrates the relative relationships between each regression model (and FS method) across the full range of features by RSQ and notes an overall positive initial trend hitting diminishing returns for all non DT models.

The DT models underperform somewhat comprehensively, failing to breach an RSQ of 30% at any poinnt.

The GB, RF, and LN models all ultimately climb in RSQ from 1 to 10 de-identified features, with most coming to rest (at 18 features) not far from where they sit at 10 features. The two highest scoring models are RF+MI and GB+CR.

The GB+CR model gets the highest r-squared from the lowest number of features, with the RF MI getting the most from an additional 6 features. It is noted that across the sample there is an inconsistent and shifting gradient for most models demonstrating a very non-linear pattern as features are included and excluded.

*From this point the two models whose RSQ warrant further testing and cross-validation are the RF+MI and GB+CR models. The full set of resuts is indexed in Appendix C.*

Part 2.2: Fine tuning and Performance Analysis¶

Random Forest and Gradient Boosting regressions have each been cross-paired with randomized and grid search cross-validation methods as well as cv-scoring to provide a three-way review on both RF + MI and GB + CR models. Utilising three models for each intends to derive a consensus opinion towards how each model scores as benchmarked against their optimal search results above.

CV Scores indicate a mean r-squared value across different folds of the data. This kneading technique of sampling and re-sampling provides different points of contrast for each model and...

The randomized search method offers a less computationally intensive approach, whereas the grid-search offers a more comprehensive brute force which is not unreasonable given the limited data size which is more accessible due to the lower numer of samples in the data.

The cross-validation here-in utilised the optimal number of features as discovered above.

# DEF FUN FOR PAIR T TEST
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import ttest_rel

def paired_t_test(dataframe, col1, col2):
    alpha=0.05
    t_statistic, p_value = ttest_rel(dataframe[col1], dataframe[col2])
    p_value = round(p_value, 2)

    if p_value < alpha:
        print(f"Statistically significant difference between {col1} and {col2} with p-value: {p_value}")
    else:
        print(f"No statistically significant difference between {col1} and {col2} with p-value: {p_value}")

Part 2.3.5: Commentary Regarding Paired T-test Results¶

For Paired T-Tests, the Null Hypothesis is that the mean of each paired observations differences is zero. Practically speaking, where every over estimate has an offsetting understimate across the sample (n=85) the test will fail to reject the Null for p values over significance (0.05).

The paired t-tests above indicate that on a feature for feature basis, there is a consistent and insignificant difference between the mean values of each feature pair as both CV methods have large pvalues. For this inquiry, the null is not rejected and it is determined that the net difference in importance between features is appoximately zero.

Where it has beeen noted above that certain models prioritise categorical variables over numeric, and vice-versa for others, the over-arching theme here is that there is no real mean difference in feature importance.

The idea that one model may be better based on it providing more features in line with the underlying objective of measuring non-financial risk against financial risk and reward measures is not supported with these data as the models who appeared to score financial risk features higher are not different with any statistical significance.

The t-tests regard predictions also demonstrate an overall insignificant difference among the 85 predictions per model per method. All pvalues against the benchmark were high for this inquiry as well. The null is not rejected and it is determined that the net difference between predictions based on each CV model compared to its benchmark is appoximately zero.

The models discovered in the feature selection process in Part 2.1 are determined to have no significant differences in predictions or feature importance having utilised Grid and Random seaching across 5 folds.

Part 3: Discussion of Limitations and Critiques¶

Part 3.1: Data Limitations¶

The data aggregated were derived from freely available sources which offer constraints to both quality and quantity.

The script to scrape the ESG scores took 14 hours to run and failed repeatedly on the uptake.

The sample itself (n~501) represents only a relatively small portion of all listed global equities and was further reduced when complete cases were considered.

The data used for modelling has been aggregated from free online sources and at the outset, the sample of 500 index consitutents is already quite small (considering all listed global equities), before being further reduced with some data unavailable at the time of collection. The data that has been aggregated is proprietary in nature, the model would be enhanced by having a full and complete access to that provided by Sustainalytics.

The ESG data anaylsed has been scored by one company only, and for a relative comparison having similar data from alternative providers would add insight into whether or not there are thematic bias present between ratings agencies.

The financial risk metrics that have been consdered for this report are limited, and nowhere close to representative of the full-suite of financial risk and reward meterics that may otherwise by used as predictor values. For scalability a comprehensive set of ratio and metric may include those in the curriculum defined by the Chartered Financial Analyst society.

The financial risk and reward metrics are additionally static calcuations over arbitrary periods of time. For added granularity in future studies it may be of value to note different lengths of time for both cumulative and periodic stretches. An example of this may be log returns for 3 years measured by year 0-1, 1-2, 2-3, or over different horizons (0-1,0-3,0-5) and so on.

Added granularity may also be defined by decomposing ratios out and using both numerator and denominator for individual features so as to avoid instances where the inter-relationship of individual features is compressed due to the relativity of their involvement.

Imputation of missing values was not considered for the reason that each observation was from 1 of 11 sectors who had unevely distributed sizes and imputing the conditional mean from a less represented sector would impact the overall accuracy when comparing those values against imputed values from sectors with higher representation.

The source of the data includes unique keys which have since changed creating a moving target for future iterations which would be solved by having a living index of stock symbols that have changed values.

Part 3.2: Model Limitation¶

The method of prediction itself relies on defining a continuous variable for predictions. Sustainalytics have denominated their scoring into brackets (negligible: 0-10, low: 10-20, moderate: 20-30, high: 30-40, and extreme >40), future iterations or derivatives of this research may focus on binning companies into one of these categorical variables which will unlock other non-utilised machine learning methods to further explore which features are highlighted from different methods to provide a more comphrehensive concsesus opinion on what matters most to predicting the total ESG scores.

The total ESG score predicted is a sum of Environmental, Social, and Governance scores, which have not been invetigated. Magnifying the complexity of this study may see the individual predictions of E,S,G scores to then utilise a paired t-test on this sum of parts relative to that provided.

A specific score may add a granular level, however, where there is low scoring accuracy as determined in Part 2, the bucketing approach may induce less bucketing error. Predicted scores that are just reaching into a higher or lower band, with lower model accuracy, may be more appropriately classified by widening the goal posts.

Four regression methods were utilised to predict the continuous variables. These were then tested by two feature selection methods and two cross-validation techniques (Grid Search and Random Search). Other vross-validation techniques, like AUC for example, may provide a more diversified approach to reviewing the best in class models.

By scoring all RSQ values by number of features by regression type the top two scoring models were chosed for cross validation. Some models scored erronous RSQ values and were dropped, whereas other models remain untested. For a more computationally exhaustive approach one may review each reasonable iteration in order to define the list of all models and all methods.

Results may vary where the selection was determined entirely on MAE, or additional metrics like Mean Squared Error, or Root Mean Squared Error, for example.

In the data aggregated in Part 2.2 the Random Forest model with Correlation based Feature selection was the second unique model type (at 18 features) but explained just over 2% less variation via RSQ relative to the Gradient Boosting model which was investigated.

Parameters for cross-validation were set to defaults, as well as 5 folds being used over the sample. Future iterations may benefit from a more engineering-based approach where the folds and the cv parameters were mixed and matched. A critique on this would be the ability to have consistency across the parameters and folds would drive a growing possible number of iterations to rank. Where it was clear that the paramters were both different to default and consistent across that search then a rule of thumb may lightle be applied, whereas without this certainty the apples for apples comparision will be difficult to determine.

Part 4: DISCUSSION¶

Task 4.1: Project Summary¶

The Phase 1 review and Phase 2 overview provide a somewhat comprehensive step-through on the steps taken. The project goal was to review the predicion of non-financial risk metrics (ESG Scores) based on Financial Risk and Reward Measures.

Task 4.2: Project Findings¶

Through the process it has been determined that the Random Forest Regession model utilising Mutual Information Feature Selection across 16 features had the highest predictive ability (46.4443%).

This model was then cross-validated using random and grid search cv methods, where the Randomised search delivered RSQ and CR measures only relatively worse than the benchmark result. This was performed on 5 folds only and may be explained due to the uneven representation within the sample between sector based categorical variables.

The deviation betwen best and worst CV score was higher for the RF model, as indicated in the Table 2.2.5, almost 6.5% of explanatory measure was reduced when utilising GS CV for the RF model. It may be possible to consider that utilisting 16 of 18 feautures in three different ways assists understanding the significance of the more and less important features defined in Part 2.2.1 and 2.2.2.

Considering the dispersion in performance scoring for RF, GB models had a tigher grouping on the target with RSQ of; 0.455154 (GB+CR), and 0.418683 (GB+RS & GB+GS).

It was noted early in Part 2.1 that looking at the data through a less sophisticated model (LN), there was a clean difference in the decay between Correlation (exponential) and Mutual Information (linear) based feature selection methods with uniquely ranked features by importance.

Following this same logic, both GB CV models held Market Capitalisation and Beta to be the two most important variables, where as RF CV models split the difference with GS finding most importance with 3 and 1 year standard devation measures on close price, whereas the RS CV method pinpointed 3 year Standard Deviation and Earnings Per Share as the top two financial risk measures (Information Technology Section scoring incrementally higher than EPS).

In the case of the RF models, there was no statistically significant difference between either of the feature importance in CV testing as well as no statistically significant evidence to suggest non-zero differences between predictions across the 85 testing points from CV to benchmark respectively. For this reason, choosing the RF model with MI FS at the highest RSQ and lowest MAE appears the best overall selection for prediction.

Part 4.3: Conclusions¶

This project has determined that across the relevant sample, the Random Forest regressor utilising Mutal Information feature selection can explain the variation in total esg scores with approximately 46% accuracy. While this is lower than that of flipping an actual coin, it is important to consider that the purpose of providing non-financial risk metrics (ESG scores) is intended to diversify the underlying thought process for end users when screening and selecting securities for their utilisation insofar that the anticipated score for such an experiment was initially expected to be much closer to zero.

The sector based categorical variables were consistently present when ranking best features and indicate that, at least among this subset of the SP500 index, the sector you operate is in itself a reaonsable explainer to your overall total score - for better and worse. This may add value to a consideration on whether or not there is merit to the 'best of the worst' being relatively better than the 'worst of the best' where two companies from differing sectors are contrast upon one another.

The financial risk variables were highest scoring, with Standard Deviation of close price being in the first few best features for each model. Financial reward (log returns) were less present in the important features at cross-validation stage and feature selection stages. The deviations and variability as explained by the 'risk' portion make more sense when considering the reflexive nature of investment market participants towards index constituents whose ESG score may infer there to be financial risk by-proxy to the non-financial risk.

A quick example may be where a company with high ESG scores is also subject to market drawdowns more frequently (and higher standard deviation) in line with their inability to run a less-risky business.

At a starting point, a 46.5% accuracy provides a benchmark for future iterations on similar methodology where the number and manner of features may be modified further.
